David Stanek wrote:
&gt;
&gt; Maybe my misunderstanding is because of the experimenting I have been
&gt; doing with Varnish. What Varnish seems to do is keep a hash of the
&gt; URL and associate any variants (using the Vary header) to that hash.
&gt; It will not go back to the origin server even after a different
&gt; variant was accessed. Once I had the text/plain version of /test in
&gt; cache Varnish always returned it even after I curl-ed for the
&gt; text/html variant of the resource. I was then able to purge /test to
&gt; rinse and repeat.
&gt; 
&gt; Is this non-compliant behavior?
&gt; 

I say unspecified behavior.  All caches behave the same way in the
presence of Content-Location, such behavior is specified.  Any cache
developer attempting to work around a missing Content-Location header,
has to choose between different unspecified behaviors.

-Eric
